Citations
Date: 0/0/1988
Source: Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author: McGILL
Vol / Page: 104
Edition:
Quote:  <i>slinter</i>, sometimes<i> slanter</i>, occasionally <i>shlanter</i>, a trick; adapted from `sclenter' or `slenter', probably Afrikaans or Dutch for an untrustworthy person on South African diamond fields; eg Gordon Slatter's <i>A Gun in My Hand:</i> `Wolkinson ... worked a slinter at the end.'
Notes:

Date: 0/7/1983
Source: Metro
Author:
Vol / Page: no.25 81
Edition:
Quote: Origin only to be guessed at. A false call or call where the driver can't locate the person who ordered the cab. Can be used as a noun - `It's a slinter'; adjectivally - `The slintered car will get the next job'; or as a verb - `I've been slintered'.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1945
Source: NZ Geographer
Author:
Vol / Page: 39
Edition:
Quote: Other unusual words are explained in the text, except perhaps one or two which are in almost universal use in New Zealand ... Finally there is `slinter' which alone presented the editor with any difficulty. To `work a slinter' apparently is - to utilize alien idiom - to `pull a fast one'
Notes:  (Cumberland's Note to Pascoe's article)

Date: 0/0/1959
Source: Gun in My Hand, A
Author: SLATTER
Vol / Page: 166
Edition:
Quote: That bloody Wilkinson. Cunning sod. He worked a slinter at the end. Ref shoulda penalised him for deliberate infringement of the rules.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Australian & NZ English [TS]
Author: SYDER & HODGETTS
Vol / Page: 1102
Edition:
Quote: To make a gain through the deception or trickery at the expense of another, but not in a serious way entailing heavy loss. .in 4;`He's worked a slinter there. I see he's used up his old supply of screws instead of the brass ones I said I wanted.'
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Islands
Author:
Vol / Page: 7/91
Edition:
Quote: It was Brixton's habit - talking to himself, a long monologue which reproduced the slang of forty years ago. Sometimes in the company of somebody younger he might for a change talk it out loud, tell about some bloke he had a snitcher on, some joker who would work a slinter if you didn't watch out - or he might start poking borax.
Notes: Sargeson (Brixton)

Date: 0/0/1976
Source: Sunset Village
Author: SARGESON
Vol / Page: 29
Edition:
Quote: It was Brixton's habit, this talking to himself, a long monologue which reproduced the slang of forty years ago. Sometimes ... he might ... tell about some bloke he had a snitcher on, or some joker [30] with the bad habit of poking borax, or he might work a slinter if you gave him half the chance.
Notes:

